[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]FPA and Brook [bold][OLS0066][bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]About FPA[bold]&#xa0;[bold]FPA is one of the UK’s leading sexual health charities. Our mission is to help establish a society in which everyone has positive, informed and non-judgmental attitudes to sex and relationships; where everyone can make informed choices about sex and reprod
[normal]uction so that they can enjoy sexual health free from prejudice or harm. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We do this through providing a comprehensive sexual health information service for professionals and the public, running community based sex and relationships education programmes a
[normal]nd campaigning to ensure that high quality sexual health information and services are available to all who need them. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To find out more about FPA and the work we do please visit our website: 
[normal]www.fpa.org.uk
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About Br[bold]ook[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Brook is the UK’s leading provider of sexual health services and advice for young people under 25. Our mission is to ensure young people can enjoy their sexuality without harm.
[normal] [bold]Brook services provide free and confidential sexual health information, co
[normal]ntraception, pregnancy testing, advice and counselling, testing and treatment for sexually transmitted infections and outreach and education work, reaching over 290,000 young people every year. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Brook believes that every young person in Britain deserves 
[normal]sex and relationships education (SRE) that is relevant to them, focuses on relationships as well as sex, honest about human sexuality and taught by professionals who are well prepared and confident. Sex and relationships are a life skill, as important to o
[normal]ur future health and happiness as any other subject, and young people deserve to be heard.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To find out more about Brook visit: 
[normal]www.brook.org.uk
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Brook and FPA 
[normal]welcome the focus on pr
[normal]otecting young
[normal] people from harm. Young people are vulnerable from online environments in a number of ways, which are not just about access to pornography. These include grooming, bullying and exploitation, and it is important that this Inquiry does not seek to dispropor
[normal]tionately focus on pornography in comparison to these other important areas of consideration. Certainly,
[normal] we know that 
[normal]simply blocking internet content is not a cure-all
[normal], and the role of education 
[normal]in supporting young people’s safe navigation of the online e
[normal]nvironment 
[normal]is 
[normal]key
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore we
[normal] strongly advise for the need to
[normal] talk about education for young people and support for parents at the same time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In particular, w
[normal]e would be concerned if actions resulting from a review of filtering
[normal] meant that legitimate educ
[normal]atio
[normal]n websites
[normal] were blocked
[normal] as well.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In summary:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Brook’s young people’s response to [bold]this Inquiry[bold]&#xa0;[bold]To inform this response, Brook asked
[normal] groups of young people across the country to consider their views of the questions and th
[normal]emes raised in this Inquiry
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]These groups included young people who identified as LGB and T
[normal] (Lesbian, Gay Bisexual and Transgender)
[normal], male, female and non-binary, 
[normal]BME
[normal] (Black, Minority, 
[normal]Ethnic
[normal] communities)
[normal], experience of mental health, experience of homelessness, and as young offenders. A summary of their conclusions is provided here and a full copy of the report can be found in Annex A of this document.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusio
[normal]ns from young people’s response
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“If young people want to access porn, out of arousal or curiosity, that's perfectly healthy and typical. However, easy access to porn needs to be supplemented with good sex education and lessons about internet awareness and
[normal] safety, as well as an open and non-judgemental societal attitude towards sex and sexuality.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](
[normal]anonymised
[normal] quote from young people’s response)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The feedback from the young people shows that, broadly speaking, 
[normal]it is clear that
[normal] young people need better, more
[normal] inclusive education on internet safety, both for children and for parents, 
[normal]not least 
[normal]to ensure that knowledge, skills and understanding around online safety are embedded in the next generation. This would support a societal shift in the bullying culture w
[normal]hich has developed around social media, without imposing enforced censorship which could inhibit young people’s ability to access accurate information about sex. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Compulsory education on internet safety, covering issues which include pornography and cyber
[normal] bullying, would allow young people to explore and understand their developing sexuality whilst reducing any risk of harm.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RESPONSE TO QUESTIONS[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1. [bold]How best to protect minors from accessing adult content?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1 
[normal]In order to protect minors from accessing adult content 
[normal]we must provide young people with the support, education, skills and understan
[normal]ding to ensure that they
[normal] are not damaged by, pressured into or exploited through exposure to porn and that they are able t
[normal]o cope with the availability of pornography, on and offline. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2 
[normal]However, 
[normal]Brook and FPA do not believe that it is possible or right to simply prevent young people 
[normal]accessing pornography. 
[normal]We make a clear distinction between child abuse and pornography, and indeed censorship and protection. 
[normal]We 
[normal]also 
[normal]welcome
[normal] the focus 
[normal]of this Inquiry 
[normal]on protecting you
[normal]ng people from harm and condemn
[normal] all images of child abuse
[normal],
[normal] which are illegal. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3 
[normal]Brook’s re
[normal]search with
[normal] [bold]groups of young people suggests:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4 
[normal]In terms of how young people would like to better deal with 
[normal]pornography they may see, 
[normal]Brook and FPA recommend
[normal] an educational approach which helps young people to:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parents
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5 
[normal]Brook and FPA 
[normal]believe
[normal] that parents should be better enabled and encouraged to
[normal] take responsibility for supervising their children and setting appropriate safety settings
[normal],
[normal] particularly
[normal] if they have young children who may be vulnerable
[normal] to seeing images that 
[normal]they 
[normal]might find
[normal] distressing. The young people 
[normal]we spoke with 
[normal]pointed out that there are existing safety settings which are very good 
[normal]filters
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]They felt that if safety settings are used appropriately then young people would not come across adult content when searching for 
[normal]something else.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“We don't need to create new 
[normal]filters,
[normal] we just need to educate parents about how to use existing safety settings.” 
[normal]Young woman, 16.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Educate the parents, who can in turn educate the children.” 
[normal]Young person, 18.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.6 
[normal]To enable parents to 
[normal]act accordingly, they suggested that education should be provided to parents so that they are able to understand and set parent
[normal]al controls. The young people that Brook
[normal] spoke to all knew how to 
[normal]set controls
[normal] themselves, describing the process as simple, and 
[normal]felt that 
[normal]with the right level of intervention and education from parents, 
[normal]there should be no reason why children should see adult content if they 
[normal]or their parents deem the material disturbing
[normal]. 
[normal]They suggested developing leaflets, posters or training/workshops for parents, explaining how simple it is to set these controls. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Educate parents on how young people access what they do and make it so that young people know that they can talk to their p
[normal]arents or someone they trust if they have seen something that makes them distressed.”
[normal] Young person, 20
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Individual guidance by parents to ensure children 
[normal]don't
[normal] find this material. If a parent is present, even if they do find it, it can be explained proper
[normal]ly, explained why it's wrong and why not to go back to the site.” 
[normal]Young person, 18.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.7 
[normal]Parenting support programmes such as the FPA’s Speakeasy
[normal] programme (see below) can help parents build up the knowledge and skills they need to enable them to discuss 
[normal]issues around sex, relationships and growing up with their children and teach them key skills in these areas. 
[normal]In turn, developing a stronger dialogue between parents and children can help build the co
[normal]nfidence of the children to
[normal] be more open with their pare
[normal]nts about what they may have seen.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Speakeasy
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.8 
[normal]Speakeasy
[normal] is a FPA course for parents and carers to better enable them to engage with the children for 
[normal]wh
[normal]ich
[normal] they are responsible, on
[normal] often tric
[normal]ky issues surrounding
[normal] sex and relationships. FPA knows that many parents and carers want to talk with their children about issues associated with growing up, including sex and relationships, but many are embarrassed or unsure about where to start and what to say. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.9 
[normal]FPA has
[normal] developed the Speakeasy programme to enable parents and carers to develop the skills, knowledge and confidence to have these sometimes difficult conversations. The community-based project runs over eight weeks and covers factual information including how 
[normal]to keep children and young people safe; the pressures young people may be under; and strategies for proactively starting 
[normal]discussions on growing up, sex and relationships. The course is accredited by the Open College Network, which gives parents the opportu
[normal]nity to receive credits for the work they do, which they can then apply in further learning or in employment. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.10 
[normal]Evaluations of the project have demonstrated the positive impact it has on parents’ knowledge, confidence and their relationships with thei
[normal]r children. A Social Return on Investment (SROI) analysis of the programme has estimated the total value of benefits to children and parents and to the state to be £21 million. The value to the state represents a return of £5.29 for every pound of public m
[normal]oney invested in the project. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sex and Rela
[normal]t
[normal]ionships Education 
[normal](SRE) 
[normal]and the role of s
[normal]chools
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.11 
[normal]Brook and FPA believe that parents and 
[normal]carers
[normal] play a crucial role in giving information and advice to children and young people about sex, relationships and
[normal] growing up. However, a
[normal]lthough parents and 
[normal]carers
[normal] absolutely have a role to play in protecting minors from accessing potentially damaging online material, according to the National Association of Head Teachers, 83% of parents also had sufficient confidence
[normal] in schools' ability to help their children understand the dangers specifically associated with pornography, and that they believed teachers were as important as parents in handling the issue. Just 13% thought it should be left to parents alone to educate 
[normal]children about pornography (NAHT survey, May 2013)
[normal] 
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.12 
[normal]Indeed, Brook and FPA strongly believe SRE must cove
[normal]r many issues relating to this I
[normal]nquiry beyond porn, including 
[normal]sexting
[normal], making friends and relationships online, bullying, and safety in relationships. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.13 
[normal]In order to achieve this, 
[normal]Brook 
[normal]and 
[normal]FPA 
[normal]be
[normal]lieve that the best strategy
[normal] is a joint home-school programme between schools, parents 
[normal]and young people. 
[normal]We should also acknowledge that many parents, despite the
[normal]ir
[normal] best intentions, will still fee
[normal]l
[normal] too awkward to have conversation
[normal]s
[normal] about sex with their children. Furthermore, schools are widely
[normal] regarded as an 
[normal]appropriate and 
[normal]impartial ground 
[normal]for such discussions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.14 
[normal]This sentiment is supported by Brook’s discussion with young people who said that
[normal] internet safety should be 
[normal]taught in school, including about
[normal] how to set controls. Brook and FPA support the young people’s suggestion that educator
[normal]s could explain to children that there are images on the internet which may not be suitable, talk to them about what it means, and teach them how to avoid it. Furthermore, children should be taught that there are some things on the internet that they may f
[normal]ind disturbing and that there are 
[normal]people they can talk to if they do see something that upsets
[normal] them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“
[normal]I think education is more important than sheltering young people and just pretending they are not there, because they would no doubt find them anyway.”
[normal] 
[normal]Y
[normal]oung Person, 18.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Better education in schools. Explain to them that those films are not real, and are actors.”
[normal] 
[normal]Young person, 20.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“I think educating young people on the different types of images etc is also important to ensure that when they are faced with such things they know how to deal with them.” 
[normal]Young person, 23.
